entry.title: Resend update-engine request when IDLE signal is received
entry.content:
A request to update will always receive a non-IDLE signal response,

followed by IDLE once the engine is ready to receive the next request.

If we receive IDLE before we have received non-IDLE, then we should

resend the request. Either (1) our request was sent while another

request was in-progress, or (2) we received a prior signal just before

sending our request. For (1), we must resend, for (2) it is safe to do

so since the duplicate request will be ignored if the first is still

in-progress, or a subsequent request to update will not cause any

problem.



The associated bug shows that tests were failing when a DLC install

request is sent prior to the update since the engine is already busy

and ignores the update request. This CL now causes chrome to resend

the update request once the engine goes back to idle.



Bug: b/279088859

entry.title: visual-debugger: Support buffer dumping with videos on Windows
entry.content:
Pages with YUV videos cause two issues with the Visual Debugger GPU

texture dumping code:

- Video overlays on Windows cause the root surface to render using

DComp surfaces. The SI backing for these surfaces set up a special

GLSurface that must be alive during the SkiaRepresentation write

access. AttemptDebuggerBufferCapture changes the current context,

which trips an assertion in our SI representation's EndWrite.

- Non-multi-planar SI for YUV textures do not set a color space for

each of the SI planes. An invalid gfx::ColorSpace turns into a

nullptr SkColorSpace, which AttemptDebuggerBufferCapture attempts

to dereference unconditionally.

entry.title: Add popover hover triggering to buttons
entry.content:
This is a semi-revert of [1], bringing back hover triggering for

popovers, including hints. Quite a few things have changed since [1]

landed, so this is mostly a re-implementation of hover triggering.

One big change is that hover triggering is only supported/possible on

a button element, rather than on any Element. This is to improve the

accessibility of this feature in case the user isn't using a mouse,

since the button will fall back to "regular" invoking behavior.



This capability is gated behind the HTMLPopoverHint feature.

need to fallback to the default renderer (e.g. Widevine content), so

entry.title: Fix GetDisplayDRM bug in fake_drv_video_unittest
entry.content:
Previously the fake_drv_video_unittest used a file descriptor of 0 in

the call to vaGetDisplayDRM during setup. For some reason this started

failing which led all the unit test checks to fail.



This update parses drm cards available to the system and attempts to get

a file descriptor for one available to feed into the vaGetDisplayDRM

function call.



This update results in all tests in the fake_drv_video_unittest passing.



BUG=b:261660716

entry.title: Fix app list presenter test
entry.content:
Ensure test suites within app_list_presenter_unittests.cc file behave correctly when the feature for app list refactoring is enabled.



Within these tests, the Screen rotation tests are the one who had significantly different results for the feature enabled/disabled. The DragController would always get the drag sequence interrupted when the screen rotates, which means that the apps grid would also need to interrupt the drag. In contrast, when the feature is disabled, the drag may be able to continue if the screen gets rotated.



As for the Item destruction, if an app list item is destroyed during a drag sequence, the controller may be able to carry on with the drag but the apps grid need to be notified of the item destruction in order to end the drag on their flow and prevent further errors to arise.

entry.title: Add checks for WebUI scheme when enabling WebUI bindings.
entry.content:
WebUI uses the concept of bindings to enable renderer-side

access to APIs such as chrome.send() or Mojo. Historically,

we have used these bindings for performing security checks

as that was a way to distinguish whether a process is for

a WebUI (and therefore privileged) or not.



At this point in time we rely on site isolation to lock all

WebUI processes to their site, so this CL is adding checks

to ensure this is always the case. Once this has been

confirmed, we can remove the security checks based on

bindings and purely rely on ProcessLock checks and site

isolation.

In some edge cases, shelf widget may receive SHOW_PRESS gesture just as

shelf layout manager as a no-op (instead of treating it as an unexpected

gesture event that cancels drag).

entry.title: Workaround for delete all delegation to Android
entry.content:
Currently Android and Chrome have different matching behaviors when both

`origins` and `domains` are empty.

Chrome: Delete -> Delete nothing; Preserve -> Delete all.

Android: Delete -> Delete all; Preserve -> Delete nothing.



Android may fix the behavior in next release. As a workaround, Chrome

will not call Android if it's to delete nothing (no-op), and call

Android with both Delete and Preserve modes if it's to delete all. These

two modes will be one no-op and one delete all in Android releases with

and without the fix.



We may consider removing this workaround when Android fix is fully

released.

entry.title: [Extensions] Prevent active tab from persisting unexpectedly.
entry.content:
When granting user site permissions we also grant active tab. Before

this change we never revoked active tab when we revoked user site

permissions. This allowed an extension to retain access in the tab where

the user site permissions were allowed.



After this change the active tab is removed when we revoke user site

permissions.



For testing I've written test cases for two scenarios.

revoke_execute_on_click is for an extension that uses

chrome.scripting.executeScript() to inject which closely mimics the

extension that exposed the bug. content_script_at_end is for a content

script injection. I additionally added a test case for

revoke_execute_on_click where grant active tab is set independently of

user site permissions so that we confirm it is removed then too.

entry.title: [Extensions] Fix service worker webRequest hang
entry.content:
If an extension registers an event listener asynchronously, it prevents

the browser from properly dispatching the event to it when the context

restarts (because the event listener may not be registered).



In the case of the webRequest API, this can result in page hangs, since

the API may need to wait for the response from an event listener before

continuing.



We previously (crrev.com/181bd4ec41) added code to the WebRequest API

to handle cases where we detected that the event wouldn't dispatch in

the extension context. However, our code detecting the event wouldn't

dispatch was incomplete: it only checked that *a* listener existed in

the process, rather than that a listener for the given event existed.

This meant that hangs were still possible if an extension registered

for multiple events, some asynchronously.



Fix this by checking for the appropriate event in the EventRouter

before dispatching. Modify an existing test to exercise this case as

well.
